{
  "id": "angular-kinematics",
  "title": "Rotational kinematics: the same calculus, angular labels",
  "topic": "rotation",
  "slug": "angular-kinematics",
  "scenario": "A flywheel starts from rest and spins up under a constant angular acceleration $\\alpha = 3$ rad/s² for $4$ s. How fast is it turning, and how many revolutions has it made? The rotational kinematics are the straight-line equations with angular symbols — step them and watch the timeless equation fall out of the integrals.",
  "regime": 1,
  "constants": {
    "theta0": 0.0,
    "omega0": 0.0,
    "alpha": 3.0
  },
  "initial_conditions": {
    "theta0": 0.0,
    "omega0": 0.0
  },
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "Constant angular acceleration (a constant net torque on a rigid body of fixed moment of inertia).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "Rigid body; angles in radians; the axis of rotation is fixed.",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
  "algebra": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "What the algebra-based course hands you (the same four equations, angular)",
        "latex": "\\omega = \\omega_0 + \\alpha t,\\quad \\theta = \\theta_0 + \\omega_0 t + \\tfrac12\\alpha t^2,\\quad \\omega^2 = \\omega_0^2 + 2\\alpha\\Delta\\theta",
        "prose": "The rotational kinematics formulas are the straight-line ones with every symbol swapped for its angular twin: $x\\to\\theta$, $v\\to\\omega$, $a\\to\\alpha$. They are memorized as a separate set — but they are the same calculus."
      }
    ],
    "result": {
      "angle": {
        "label": "Angle turned $\\theta(T)$",
        "unit": "rad",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\frac{\\alpha t^{2}}{2} + \\omega_{0} t + \\theta_{0}",
        "value": 24.0,
        "display": "24"
      },
      "final_omega": {
        "label": "Final angular velocity $\\omega(T)$",
        "unit": "rad/s",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\alpha t + \\omega_{0}",
        "value": 12.0,
        "display": "12"
      },
      "revolutions": {
        "label": "Revolutions $\\theta/2\\pi$",
        "unit": "rev",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\frac{\\frac{\\alpha t^{2}}{2} + \\omega_{0} t + \\theta_{0}}{2 \\pi}",
        "value": 3.819719,
        "display": "3.82"
      }
    }
  },
  "calculus": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Constant angular acceleration",
        "latex": "\\alpha = \\text{const} \\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad \\omega(t) = \\omega_0 + \\int_0^t \\alpha\\,dt' = \\omega_0 + \\alpha t",
        "prose": "A constant net torque gives a constant angular acceleration. Integrate it once for the angular velocity — exactly as constant linear acceleration integrates to $v$."
      },
      {
        "label": "Integrate again for the angle",
        "latex": "\\theta(t) = \\theta_0 + \\int_0^t \\omega\\,dt' = \\theta_0 + \\omega_0 t + \\tfrac12\\alpha t^2",
        "prose": "Integrate the angular velocity for the angle. This is the rotational $x = x_0 + v_0 t + \\tfrac12 a t^2$ — the area under the $\\omega$–$t$ line is the angle turned."
      },
      {
        "label": "The timeless equation falls out",
        "latex": "\\boxed{\\,\\omega^2 = \\omega_0^2 + 2\\alpha\\,\\Delta\\theta\\,}",
        "prose": "Eliminate $t$ between the two integrals and the memorized timeless equation appears — and SymPy proves it. Nothing about rotation is new; it is constant-acceleration kinematics with angular labels.",
        "emphasis": true
      }
    ]
  },
  "proof": {
    "kind": "equivalence",
    "heading": "The rotational equations are the linear ones with angular symbols — and the timeless equation falls out of the integrals.",
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true,
    "detail": "check $\\theta' = \\omega$ and $\\omega' = \\alpha$; show $\\omega^2 = \\omega_0^2 + 2\\alpha\\Delta\\theta$ and $\\Delta\\theta = \\tfrac12(\\omega_0+\\omega)t$ fall out",
    "checks": [
      {
        "key": "omega_is_integral",
        "claim": "Angular velocity is the integral of $\\alpha$: $\\omega = d\\theta/dt$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "alpha_constant",
        "claim": "Angular acceleration is constant: $\\alpha = d\\omega/dt$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "timeless_falls_out",
        "claim": "The memorized timeless equation $\\omega^2 = \\omega_0^2 + 2\\alpha\\,\\Delta\\theta$ falls out.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "average_velocity",
        "claim": "The average-velocity relation $\\Delta\\theta = \\tfrac12(\\omega_0+\\omega)\\,t$ holds.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      }
    ]
  },
